		<content type="html" xml:base="http://skysedge.us/forum/viewtopic.php?t=1482&amp;p=1520#p1520"><![CDATA[
KiCad has come a long way but I personally don't like that they rely on external BOM generation scripts to generate CSVs, and on Linux none seem to get installed by default.<br><br>I recently learned of another way of getting a BOM out of it that's actually pretty easy, but you'd never really think to do it this way. In the schematic editor go to Tools &gt; Edit Symbol Fields. This presents you with a spreadsheet which is in effect a BOM, and you can pick and choose what fields you want with the left pane. To extract it I just select all and paste into a spreadsheet or text editor. <br><br>It's meant for editing symbol values all in one place of course (changes propagate back to the schematic), which is also handy.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://skysedge.us/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=2">justine</a> — Sat Apr 25, 2020 8:48 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
